al issue, the demand for desalination technology is expected to continue rising, leading to an expansion in the use of RO membranes in this sector.</p><h2>RO Purification Systems</h2><p>Reverse Osmosis (RO) purification systems are widely used in residential, commercial, and industrial applications to provide clean and safe drinking water. These systems use RO membranes to remove contaminants, including salts, chemicals, bacteria, and viruses, from water sources. As urbanization accelerates and environmental concerns intensify, there is an increasing demand for point-of-use (POU) water treatment solutions. RO systems in household water filtration devices are gaining popularity for their effectiveness in providing high-quality purified water. Commercial establishments, including restaurants, hotels, and offices, are also incorporating RO purification systems to ensure safe drinking water for their customers and staff.</p><p>The growth of the RO purification systems segment is driven by a rising awareness of water contamination risks and the need for advanced filtration technologies. In industrial applications, RO systems are utilized for process water treatment, reducing the need for chemical treatments and ensuring high-quality water for operations. Additionally, the growing demand for bottled water and the expansion of global water treatment infrastructure contribute to the increased adoption of RO purification systems. These systems are valued for their ability to efficiently remove a wide range of contaminants, ensuring water safety and quality across various applications.</p><h2>Others</h2><p>The "Others" segment of the RO artificial membrane market encompasses a variety of specialized applications where RO membranes are used for purposes beyond desalination and water purification. These applications include wastewater treatment, food and beverage processing, pharmaceutical manufacturing, and various industrial processes. In wastewater treatment, RO membranes pl